Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula says the deadline has been pushed back by two extra weeks. JOHANNESBURG - The process that could see e-tolls scrapped permanently has been postponed. Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula says the deadline has been pushed back by two extra weeks. Mbalula says this is to allow for more consultations. READ: Finance Minister slams Sanral's e-toll decision The minister will meet with civil society groups such as AA and OUTA . Sanral is owed close to R11-billion in unpaid e-toll fees. In July President Cyril Ramaphosa tasked the finance minister to work with Gauteng Premier David Makhura to find a solution to e-tolls.